# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1969-major-league-baseball-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The **1878 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1878, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the third season of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1877, two teams would fold: Brooklyn Hartfords and St.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] They were replaced by the Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Later in the offseason, the Providence Grays would join on February 6, raising the number of teams to seven.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] On April 1 or 2, the Louisville Grays would officially resign from the league, once again lowering the number of teams to six.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The 1878 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] This format had been in place since the previous season, and would be the final season which saw this format, due to expansion to eight teams the following season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all six teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams hosted games at neutral sites, the Indianapolis Blues and Providence Grays.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Four tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues had three tie games.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Milwaukee Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings leave the 23rd Street Grounds (where they played for four seasons since their National Association days from 1874) and move to Lakefront Park where they would play for seven seasons through 1884.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The **1879 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1879, and saw the Providence Grays as the pennant winner of the fourth season of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League was set on expanding from a six-team league to an eight-team league.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays folded, and in its place, the league admitted the Cleveland Blues, the International Association's Buffalo Bisons and Syracuse Stars, and finally (with confirmation Milwaukee was not returning) the Troy Trojans.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] It is suggested by Society for American Baseball Research (SABR) that this season featured the first African-American to play major league baseball, William Edward White, who played one game with the Providence Grays on June 21.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] He predates brothers Moses Fleetwood Walker and Weldy Walker by five years, and Jackie Robinson by 68 years.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The 1879 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 12-games-each format that had been in place since 1877, as the National League expanded from six to eight teams, adding 24 games to each team's schedule.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring six teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] Five tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings had four tie games.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Reds, Providence Grays, and Syracuse Stars had one tie game each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1879-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at the Putnam Grounds on September 20 against the Chicago White Stockings, moving to Haymakers' Grounds for the start of the 1880 season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The **1880 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 1, 1880, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the fifth season of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 season is known for the first two major league perfect games in history, as well as being the only perfect games in the 19th century.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Thrown by Lee Richmond and John Ward, these two perfect games were thrown in the span of five days, the shortest amount of time between two perfect games (the next closest is currently 20 days between Dallas Braden's May 9 and Roy Halladay's and May 29, 2010 perfect games).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] A perfect game would not be seen again in the Major Leagues for 24 years when Cy Young threw his perfect game in 1904.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the Cincinnati Reds and Syracuse Stars disbanded, and were replaced by the Cincinnati Stars and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the Stars' only major league season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the previous season and would be used until 1883.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 1, featuring a doubleheader between the Providence Grays and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Eight tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Stars, and Providence Grays had three tie games each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, and Worcester Worcesters had two tie games each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave the Putnam Grounds (where they played their inaugural seasons) and move to the Haymakers' Grounds, where they would play for two seasons through 1881.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans begin to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on September 11.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The **1881 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through September 30, 1881, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the sixth season of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The 1881 season is most known for featuring the first major league grand slam.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Roger Connor of the Troy Trojans hit the walk-off home run at Riverside Park (Greenbush) against the Worcester Worcesters on September 10, leading to an 8–7 victory.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the National League dropped the Cincinnati Stars because the team refused to sign a league pledge that banned alcohol in league parks and forbade clubs from renting their parks out on Sundays.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The team was replaced by the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] 1881 would be the final season of the first National League monopoly-era, as the American Association would be established in 1882.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The 1881 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since 1879 and would be used until 1883.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring four teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] Two tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues, Providence Grays, Troy Trojans, and Worcester Worcesters had one tie game each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines join the National League and play at Recreation Park in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans would play their final game at Haymakers' Grounds on September 30 against the Detroit Wolverines, moving to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds for the start of the 1882 season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1881-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on June 15 and September 10.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The **1969 major league baseball season** began on April 7, 1969, while the regular season ended on October 2.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The season was celebrated as the 100th anniversary of professional baseball, honoring the first professional touring baseball team, the Cincinnati Red Stockings of 1869.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The season also brought rule changes to counteract pitchers' dominance in recent seasons, such as lowering the pitcher's mound and shrinking the height of the strike zone.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The 40th All-Star Game was held on July 23 at the Robert F.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Kennedy Memorial Stadium in Washington, D.C., home of the Washington Senators.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The season saw the third round of expansion of the decade (and second for each league), with the enfranchisement of the Kansas City Royals and Seattle Pilots in the American League and the Montreal Expos and San Diego Padres in the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Both leagues increased to 12 teams; the National League had last been so large in 1899.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season for the Pilots, as stadium problems and bankruptcy would lead them to move to Milwaukee, Wisconsin, to become the Milwaukee Brewers the following season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The expansion launched the "Divisional Era", as each league split its teams into two six-team divisions and scheduled more games between division rivals and fewer between interdivision teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Each league implemented their own League Championship Series, which saw division champions face off in a best-of-five series (increased to seven in 1985) to determine pennant winners and World Series contenders.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles won the AL East with a major-league-best 109–53 record, and then defeated the AL West champion Minnesota Twins in three games in the first American League Championship Series.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Mets won the NL East with an NL-best 100–62 record, and then defeated the NL West champion Atlanta Braves in three games in the first National League Championship Series.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The "Miracle Mets", having joined the league in 1962, were the first expansion team to win a pennant.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Bowie Kuhn was named the 5th commissioner of baseball at the start of the season replacing previous commissioner William Eckert.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Eckert was forced out by the owners in December 1968 mainly because of his refusal to cancel games in the wake of the assassinations of Robert Kennedy and Martin Luther King Jr. and for his refusal to help the owners during a player strike they anticipated was around the corner.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Kuhn was named interim commissioner during that time and became the official commissioner by the start of the season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Kuhn remains the youngest ever commissioner of baseball, being only 42 when he took office.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] MLB called for a four-team expansion to take place in 1971 at the 1967 Winter Meetings, the first expansion since 1962.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] However, there was a complication: influential U.S.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Senator Stuart Symington of Missouri was irate over the American League's approval of Kansas City Athletics owner Charles O.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Finley's arrangement to move his team to Oakland, California, for the 1968 season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] This happened even though Finley had just signed a deal to play at Municipal Stadium at AL president Joe Cronin's behest, and Jackson County, Missouri, had just issued public bonds to build a stadium, the future Royals Stadium (now Kauffman Stadium), which would be completed in 1973.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Symington drew up legislation to remove baseball's anti-trust exemption and threatened to pursue its passage if Kansas City did not get a new team.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The leagues agreed and moved expansion up to 1969, with the AL putting one of its new franchises in Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Ewing Kauffman won the bidding for that franchise, naming it the Kansas City Royals, after the local American Royal livestock show.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The other AL team was awarded to Seattle, Washington.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] A consortium led by Dewey Soriano and William Daley won the bidding for the Seattle franchise and named it the Seattle Pilots, a salute to the harbor pilots of the Puget Sound maritime industry and to the city's place in the aviation industry.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] In the NL, one franchise was awarded to San Diego, California; the other to Montreal, Quebec, resulting in the first MLB franchise outside the United States.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Arnholdt Smith, former owner of the AAA Pacific Coast League's San Diego Padres, won the bidding for the San Diego franchise, and the new San Diego MLB team inherited the *Padres* moniker.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Charles Bronfman, owner of Seagram, won the bidding for the Montreal franchise, naming them the Expos, in honor of the World's Fair that year.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last NL expansion until the 1993 season, and the last expansion for the major leagues overall until 1977.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] As part of the 1969 expansion, each league was to be split into two divisions of six teams each, with each league holding a best-of-five League Championship Series to decide the pennant.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The AL was divided purely along geographic lines, but when it came to assign divisions in the NL, the Chicago Cubs and St.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals insisted on being placed in the same division with the New York Mets and Philadelphia Phillies, on the basis that a schedule with more games with eastern teams would create a more lucrative schedule.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Thus, Atlanta and Cincinnati were placed in the NL West.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] This alignment also addressed concerns that putting the league's three strongest clubs at the time—St.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, San Francisco, and the Cubs—in the west would result in divisional inequity.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Padres and Expos each finished with 110 losses and at the bottom of their respective divisions.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Royals did better, finishing 69–93 and in fourth in the AL West, ahead of the Chicago White Sox.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The legal fallout of the battle would lead eventually to another round of expansion for the AL in the 1977 season, with Seattle getting a new team called the Mariners.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] A special silhouetted batter logo, still in use by the league today, was created by Jerry Dior to commemorate the 100th anniversary of professional baseball.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Every player and official in Major League Baseball wore a jersey patch that featured the logo and the phrase "100th anniversary" in red letters.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] It has served as inspiration for logos for other sports leagues in the United States—most notably the National Basketball Association, which used the silhouette of Jerry West to create their current logo, unveiled after the 1968–69 season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The 1969 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 12 teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Each league was split into two six-team divisions.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against their five division rivals, totaling 90 games, and 12 games against six interdivision opponents, totaling 72 games.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] This format was implemented due to expansion of each league from ten to 12 teams, and the subsequent split of each league into two divisions.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] This format would be used until 1977 in the American League and 1993 in the National League.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 7, featuring six teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2, featuring 18 teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Each League Championship Series took place between October 4 and October 6.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 11 and October 16.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox hosted 11 neutral site games throughout the season against each of the 11 other American League teams in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, the former home of the recently relocated Milwaukee Braves.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] After the 1968 season, the Major League Baseball Players' Association and the owners had concluded the first collective bargaining agreement in major league history.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] However, one point remained unresolved: the owners refused to increase their contribution to the players' pension plan commensurately with revenues from television broadcasts, which were increasing as more and more fans watched games that way.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] With the two sides at an impasse, at the beginning of the year the union called on players to refuse to sign contracts until the issue was resolved.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Many did, including stars like Brooks Robinson.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The owners did not change their position, so the players' union called for members to boycott spring training the following month if the issue had not been resolved by then.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] After the union rejected the owners' offer of a higher yet still fixed contribution on February 17, the day before spring training was to begin, 400 players refused to report.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The owners expected the situation to resolve itself soon in their favor, since they usually lost money on training camps while the players were foregoing their pay in the meantime.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The players remained united, and few changed their minds about the boycott as it progressed.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] After the first week only 11 of those who initially boycotted had reported; at the time many had off-season jobs which they continued to work at, and those who did report were in many cases not certain of their futures with their teams.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the owners were being pressured by the television broadcasters, who would also lose money without games to broadcast, or if teams played games with largely unknown rookies—one NBC executive said his company "would not pay major league prices for minor league games".
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] After that first week, new commissioner Bowie Kuhn leaned on the owners to reach an agreement as well, and they soon sat down with the players again.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] By February 25 they had acceded to most of the players' demands: a higher contribution of approximately $5.45 million annually, an earlier age at which players could begin drawing pensions, a wider range of benefits and less playing time required for eligibility.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] By the end of the month, all players had reported to spring training.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (2 in AL, 1 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The California Angels, Kansas City Royals, New York Yankees, and Seattle Pilots had one tie each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and Cincinnati Reds had one tie each.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 16 with the New York Mets defeating the Baltimore Orioles in the 1969 World Series in five games.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The pennant races in the American League lacked drama.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] In the east, the Baltimore Orioles won 109 games and won the division by a whopping 19 games over the defending world champion Detroit Tigers.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The surprise team was the "new" Washington Senators.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Under new manager Ted Williams, they went 86–76; it was their first winning season since joining the league in 1961.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Western Division race was a little closer, but the Minnesota Twins led most of the season and were never really threatened in winning the division by 9 games over the Oakland Athletics (who were the only other west team to finish over .500).
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The National League, on the other hand, was very dramatic.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs won 35 of their first 50 games, and on August 16, they led the New York Mets and St.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] But the Mets proceeded to win 37 of their last 48 games while the Cubs went 20–28 in the same time period and the Mets won the division by 8 games.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] In the West, with 3 weeks to play in the season, 5 teams were all within 2 games of each other.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Houston Astros were the first to drop out of the race, losing 8 of 10.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] With two weeks to play, the San Francisco Giants led the Los Angeles Dodgers and Atlanta Braves by ½ game while the Cincinnati Reds were 2 games back.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers then lost 8 in a row and 10 of 11 to fall to 4th place.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Braves then went on a 10-game winning streak, ultimately clinching the division over the Giants on the next to last day of the season with a 3–2 win over the Reds.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] For the Giants, it was the 5th year in a row they would finish in 2nd place.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators' District of Columbia Stadium was announced to be renamed to Robert F.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Kennedy Memorial Stadium on January 18, in the last days of the Johnson Administration, Secretary of the Interior Stewart Udall announced that the stadium would be renamed Robert F.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Kennedy Memorial Stadium, in Kennedy's honor following his assassination in 1968.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The dedication ceremony at the stadium was held several months later on June 7.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] The official renaming ceremony was held on June 7, but by then many had already been referring to it as "RFK Stadium" or simply "RFK".
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] Though accounting for only 14% of home games, these 11 games accounted for 34% of all home games attendance for the White Sox.
[src:1969-major-league-baseball-season/1969-major-league-baseball-season] NBC was the exclusive national TV broadcaster of MLB, airing the weekend *Game of the Week*, the All-Star Game, both League Championship Series, and the World Series.
